EC sensors are intriguing due to their outstanding detection capabilities, cost-effectiveness, ease of use in both experimental setups and real-time analyses, and technological advancements, setting them apart from other sensors employed across diverse research domains [146]. According to researchers, AgNPs loaded on the surface of CDs can be used as EC sensors for a wide range of (bio)molecules. Some papers reported the applications of Ag/CDs as EC sensors towards thrombin (TB), glucose, triclosan, miRNA, anthracene, and naphthalene. For example, pDNA-PDANS/Ag/CDs were prepared by Liu and colleagues and used as an EC aptamer to detect TB (PDANS refers to polydopamine nanospheres) (Fig. 10
                        ) [32]. A linear relationship between TB responses with the concentration range of 1 fmol/L to 5 nmol/L and decreased EC intensity was observed with the LOD of 0.35 fmol/L (Fig. 10A). The calibration curve for TB is shown in Fig. 10B. The working electrode was prepared by depositing the graphene-Pt (Gr-Pt) and functionalizing cDNA on a glassy C electrode to obtain cDNA-Gr-Pt (Fig. 10C). The obtained cDNA-Gr-Pt was incubated with pDNA-PDANS/Ag/CDs to hybridize on top of the electrode. After that, the TB made contact with the electrode system and identified the EC signals before and after interacting with TB (Fig. 10D). Because of their superior conductivity and accelerated electron-hole injection, AgNPs can reduce the electron-relay shield between a semiconducting EC emitter and the working electrode. Strong EC signals were obtained by introducing pDNA-PDANS/Ag/CDs into electrode interfaces by using cDNA and pDNA hybridization chain reactions. The voltage range used was -1.8 V to 0 V, and the scanning rate was 0.1 V. In the sensing mechanism, the release of pDNA from the electrode surface caused by TB bound to cDNA reduced the EC intensity. This EC sensor demonstrated high sensitivity, reproducibility, and selectivity. Besides, Zhang et al. proposed that Ag/CDs could be able to sense the H2O2 and NO2
                        - ions with the LOD of 0.51 μM and 0.48 μM [147]. Upon depositing Ag/CDs onto a graphene (GR) modified glassy C electrode (GCE), the resulting Ag/C NC/GR/GCE demonstrated remarkably rapid direct electron transfer as its sensing mechanism and commendable electrocatalytic activity for nitrite oxidation.
